        <div class="place">
        <h2><strong>India Gate</strong></h2>
            <img src="indiagate.jpg" alt="IndiaGate">
            <p>
An iconic tribute, this monument in Delhi, erected in 1931, is a symbol of India's history. The India Gate, a stunning memorial for World War I and Afghanistan war martyrs, glows with beauty at night. Frequented by locals, it stands as a must-visit attraction in Delhi, especially after sunset.</p>
        <ul class="list">
        <li><strong>Location: </strong>Rajpath Marg, New Delhi</li>
        <li><strong>Timings:</strong> Open 24*7</li>
        </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="place">
            <h2><strong>Jantar Mantar</strong></h2>
            <img src="jantarmantar.jpg" alt="JantarMantar">
           <p>Jantar Mantar, an extraordinary observatory in Delhi, is a unique blend of ancient astronomy and architectural marvel. Built in the 18th century, its massive instruments, designed by Maharaja Jai Singh II, stand as a testament to scientific ingenuity. This UNESCO World Heritage Site offers a distinctive experience, allowing visitors to explore and understand the celestial wonders through its intriguing structures. A visit to Jantar Mantar is a journey through time and knowledge, making it an exceptional attraction in Delhi.</p>
<ul class="list">
        <li><strong>Location: </strong>Sansad Marg, CP, New Delhi</li>
        <li><strong>Timings:</strong> 9:00 am to 7:00 pm</li>
        </ul>
        </div>



        <div class="place">
            <h2><strong>Red Fort</strong></h2>
            <img src="redfort.jpg" alt="RedFort">
            <p>The Red Fort, a majestic UNESCO World Heritage Site in Delhi, is an emblem of India's rich history and Mughal architecture. Built by Emperor Shah Jahan in the 17th century, its red sandstone walls stand as a symbol of power and grandeur. The fort's intricate design, including Diwan-i-Aam and Diwan-i-Khas, reflects the opulence of the Mughal era. A visit to the Red Fort offers a glimpse into India's cultural legacy and historical significance, making it a must-see landmark in Delhi</p>
            <ul class="list">
        <li><strong>Location: </strong>Netaji Subhash Marg, Lal Qila, Chandni Chowk, New Delhi.</li>
        <li><strong>Timings:</strong>9:30 am to 4:30 pm daily, Mondays closed </li>
        </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="place">
            <h2><strong>Qutub Minar</strong></h2>
            <img src="qutubminar.jpg" alt="QutubMinar">
                <p>Qutub Minar, a UNESCO World Heritage Site in Delhi, is an iconic symbol of India's architectural prowess and historical legacy. Standing at 73 meters, this towering minaret was constructed in the 12th century by Qutub-ud-din Aibak. The complex also features the Quwwat-ul-Islam Mosque, the earliest mosque built in Delhi. The intricate carvings and inscriptions on the minaret's red sandstone surface showcase a fusion of various architectural styles. A visit to Qutub Minar offers a journey through centuries of history, making it a captivating destination for history enthusiasts and tourists alike.</p>
            <ul class="list">
        <li><strong>Location: </strong> Mehrauli, New Delhi</li>
        <li><strong>Timings:</strong>7:00 am to 5:00 pm daily</li>
        </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="place">
            <h2><strong>Lotus Mahal</strong></h2>
            <img src="lm.jpg" alt="Lotus Mahal">
                <p>The Lotus Mahal, also known as the Kamal Mahal or Chitrangini Mahal, is a unique architectural gem located in Hampi, Karnataka, India. This stunning structure is part of the Zenana Enclosure, a secluded area in the royal complex. Built during the Vijayanagara Empire in the 14th to 16th centuries, the Lotus Mahal showcases a distinctive blend of Hindu and Islamic architectural styles.</p>
                <p>What sets the Lotus Mahal apart is its lotus-shaped dome and delicately arched windows, which resemble petals. The structure is made of finely carved stone and features a beautiful synthesis of functionality and aesthetic appeal. The Lotus Mahal served as a recreational palace for the royal women, offering a tranquil and elegant retreat within the grandiose Vijayanagara capital.</p>
                <p>Visitors are drawn to the Lotus Mahal not only for its architectural beauty but also for its historical significance, providing a glimpse into the sophisticated lifestyle of the Vijayanagara rulers.</p>
            <ul class="list">
        <li><strong>Location: </strong>Lotus Temple Rd, Bahapur, Shambhu Dayal Bagh, Kalkaji, New Delhi.</li>
        <li><strong>Timings:</strong>Remains open on all days except Monday. Timings in summers is 9:00 am to 7:00 pm and in winters, 9:00 am to 5:30 </li>
        </ul>
